00:11:37,260 --> 00:11:39,021
and how we work as a company.

260
00:11:39,802 --> 00:11:42,083
I'm gonna do a very short explanation

261
00:11:42,223 --> 00:11:44,205
of what Lean Startup is in our industry.

262
00:11:45,625 --> 00:11:49,246
The most prominent voice of doing lean startup

263
00:11:49,366 --> 00:11:51,066
in the games industry is Supercell.

264
00:11:51,786 --> 00:11:55,047
Supercell have a lot of speeches about this,

265
00:11:55,167 --> 00:11:56,207
a lot of public talks.

266
00:11:56,267 --> 00:11:58,008
This is a strategy that they have adopted

267
00:11:58,568 --> 00:12:00,108
and they know better than me to say how,

268
00:12:00,288 --> 00:12:01,709
so this is a link for what they do.

269
00:12:02,669 --> 00:12:05,870
The idea is when you're doing a lean startup approach

270
00:12:05,910 --> 00:12:09,051
to product design, you have a loop of stages

271
00:12:09,491 --> 00:12:10,731
that you keep doing very quickly.

272
00:12:11,131 --> 00:12:11,871
You build something.

273
00:12:12,919 --> 00:12:15,421
like a new maze, then you release it,

274
00:12:15,581 --> 00:12:17,262
you measure how people are playing that maze,

275
00:12:17,442 --> 00:12:20,044
or a new level, or a new game, and then you learn.

276
00:12:20,885 --> 00:12:22,145
You see if people are enjoying this,

277
00:12:22,206 --> 00:12:24,087
if people are not enjoying this, where it works.

278
00:12:24,447 --> 00:12:26,468
Then you build something else, and you keep that going.

279
00:12:27,229 --> 00:12:29,170
Where analytics comes into this is,

280
00:12:29,791 --> 00:12:32,553
analytics really helps you find out what doesn't work.

281
00:12:33,173 --> 00:12:34,814
The key thing about being lean,

282
00:12:35,740 --> 00:12:37,362
is not having the secret to success.

283
00:12:37,882 --> 00:12:40,184
It doesn't necessarily mean all your games will be amazing.

284
00:12:40,624 --> 00:12:41,565
What it does mean is,

285
00:12:41,985 --> 00:12:43,927
you'll find out very quickly what doesn't work.

286
00:12:44,627 --> 00:12:46,208
And this is really, really important.

287
00:12:47,189 --> 00:12:50,792
You can take a game that runs for two years development

288
00:12:50,952 --> 00:12:52,053
with a 20 people team,

289
00:12:52,673 --> 00:12:54,455
and we had this happen in SocialPoint,

290
00:12:55,075 --> 00:12:57,497
is released, and then we found some of the problems we had,

291
00:12:57,997 --> 00:13:00,099
or you can find that out with two people in three months.

292
00:13:01,350 --> 00:13:03,911
And then if that doesn't work, try something else.

293
00:13:04,192 --> 00:13:06,172
We're trying new genres, we're trying match threes,

294
00:13:06,212 --> 00:13:07,853
we're trying different themes.

295
00:13:08,733 --> 00:13:10,954
That doesn't work, you wanna switch to a different genre,

296
00:13:10,974 --> 00:13:13,335
you wanna do word puzzles, take the same theme and do that.

297
00:13:13,775 --> 00:13:16,497
But find out very quickly, if you're not reaching that,

298
00:13:16,837 --> 00:13:20,038
whatever your goal is, day one 60% retention,

299
00:13:20,518 --> 00:13:23,640
conversion of 2%, whatever you're aiming for,

300
00:13:24,020 --> 00:13:26,601
the lean startup is a way to find out very quickly,

301
00:13:27,121 --> 00:13:29,202
are you getting there, are you getting closer, or not?

302
00:13:30,263 --> 00:13:32,324
And if not, then you kill it and you move to something else.

303
00:13:33,104 --> 00:13:34,865
So the idea is to fail fast.

304
00:13:35,605 --> 00:13:36,746
Saves you time and saves you money.

305
00:13:38,006 --> 00:13:39,987
All right, Lean Analytics.

306
00:13:40,867 --> 00:13:43,388
Lean Analytics is a school within the Lean startup.

307
00:13:44,188 --> 00:13:45,769
And this is what we're gonna talk about today.

308
00:13:47,281 --> 00:13:49,663
I'm going to say a few very trivial things now.

309
00:13:50,003 --> 00:13:52,445
What I'm gonna say now in this part of the talk

310
00:13:52,625 --> 00:13:54,486
is going to be things that are very common sense.

311
00:13:54,847 --> 00:13:56,688
None of this is rocket science.

312
00:13:56,788 --> 00:13:57,889
All of these things that I'm saying

313
00:13:57,909 --> 00:13:59,630
will sound very reasonable,

314
00:13:59,771 --> 00:14:01,172
and I'm not telling you anything new.

315
00:14:02,112 --> 00:14:04,134
But this is the part where I'm talking

316
00:14:04,174 --> 00:14:05,195
about things we did wrong.

317
00:14:05,815 --> 00:14:06,996
All of these things are based

318
00:14:07,901 --> 00:14:09,562
on things that we did not implement correctly,

319
00:14:10,022 --> 00:14:11,804
things that we failed to do at SocialPoint

320
00:14:11,844 --> 00:14:13,124
and other companies that I've worked at.

321
00:14:13,565 --> 00:14:15,906
So it's really worthwhile to take these things

322
00:14:15,966 --> 00:14:16,607
and adopt them.

323
00:14:16,687 --> 00:14:19,108
This is a discipline that you have to keep.

324
00:14:19,709 --> 00:14:20,869
And I'll show you in a minute

325
00:14:21,050 --> 00:14:23,251
how we keep ourselves very disciplined.

326
00:14:25,532 --> 00:14:26,353
Measure what matters.

327
00:14:27,214 --> 00:14:30,235
This is a very nice philosophical saying,

328
00:14:30,275 --> 00:14:31,676
but what's behind it is this.

329
00:14:32,257 --> 00:14:33,598
SocialPoint at the beginning of 2018

330
00:14:34,718 --> 00:14:36,279
had more than a thousand metrics.

331
00:14:37,062 --> 00:14:39,083
We were using more than a thousand metrics

332
00:14:39,584 --> 00:14:40,884
to measure if the game was doing well.

333
00:14:41,785 --> 00:14:43,046
We had too much data.

334
00:14:43,166 --> 00:14:46,088
We had so much data, when you asked a game designer

335
00:14:46,108 --> 00:14:48,089
what they look at, every game designer

336
00:14:48,129 --> 00:14:49,129
was looking at different things.

337
00:14:50,510 --> 00:14:52,952
What we did was, we really narrowed it down.

338
00:14:53,032 --> 00:14:55,013
We asked what really is important?

339
00:14:55,493 --> 00:14:57,374
Of all these things, what makes the cut?

340
00:14:57,855 --> 00:14:59,195
What are the super KPIs?

341
00:14:59,736 --> 00:15:01,537
The core KPIs that we have to know.

342
00:15:02,177 --> 00:15:03,158
When you're driving a car,

343
00:15:03,995 --> 00:15:05,275
You only know what you need to know.

344
00:15:05,335 --> 00:15:07,396
The dashboard doesn't give you everything you need to know.

345
00:15:08,016 --> 00:15:09,616
Air pressure, the heat of the ground.

346
00:15:09,756 --> 00:15:10,977
You don't need to know all these things

347
00:15:10,997 --> 00:15:11,797
when you're doing that.

348
00:15:12,297 --> 00:15:14,538
If there's a problem, we drill down.

349
00:15:15,218 --> 00:15:16,698
But we've been able to narrow it down

350
00:15:16,758 --> 00:15:20,640
to retention, conversion, LTV.

351
00:15:21,840 --> 00:15:23,961
We've been able to talk about revenues.

352
00:15:24,121 --> 00:15:26,081
And when we talk about a very specific cost,

353
00:15:26,101 --> 00:15:27,782
by the way, some things that didn't make the cut,

354
00:15:28,302 --> 00:15:29,222
second session retention.

355
00:15:30,570 --> 00:15:33,012
We actually don't have that on the first view of a game.

356
00:15:33,032 --> 00:15:34,673
When we talk about is the game good,

357
00:15:35,154 --> 00:15:37,255
we talk about day one retention, day three retention,

358
00:15:37,295 --> 00:15:39,617
but we don't talk about a session granularity.

359
00:15:40,058 --> 00:15:42,319
Sometimes we don't even talk about a daily granularity.

360
00:15:42,359 --> 00:15:43,661
We look at it on a weekly basis.

361
00:15:44,481 --> 00:15:46,783
This was a system that was designed for the executive team

362
00:15:47,524 --> 00:15:49,185
and really created a different conversation.

363
00:15:49,545 --> 00:15:52,047
And it changed the mode from bombarded

364
00:15:52,488 --> 00:15:54,169
with million reports and million metrics

365
00:15:54,209 --> 00:15:55,891
to really focusing on what's important.

366
00:15:56,811 --> 00:15:57,452
The other thing is,

367
00:15:58,622 --> 00:15:59,722
Don't develop what you can buy.

368
00:16:00,443 --> 00:16:02,283
Now this is really true for small companies

369
00:16:02,343 --> 00:16:03,683
and it's also true for big companies.

370
00:16:05,243 --> 00:16:08,284
We have a very strong data engineering team

371
00:16:08,444 --> 00:16:10,925
and we do do a lot of our tools in-house.

372
00:16:11,545 --> 00:16:12,745
We also have scientists.

373
00:16:12,865 --> 00:16:15,145
When I do A-B tests, it's my scientists

374
00:16:15,165 --> 00:16:16,186
who create the tools for that

375
00:16:16,946 --> 00:16:18,506
and my analysts benefit from that.

376
00:16:19,166 --> 00:16:21,667
But even with that, there's things that I don't develop.

377
00:16:22,247 --> 00:16:23,987
One of the things, one of the problems that we had

378
00:16:24,567 --> 00:16:27,768
at SocialPoint, we had KPIs that were misbehaving.

379
00:16:28,660 --> 00:16:30,822
We had a process that was getting data, for example,

380
00:16:31,102 --> 00:16:33,184
AppSlayer data about user attribution.

381
00:16:33,724 --> 00:16:36,266
This was data that was telling us which user came into the

382
00:16:36,307 --> 00:16:39,329
game through which marketing campaign, which was really key

383
00:16:39,349 --> 00:16:40,790
because we spend a lot of money in marketing,

384
00:16:40,871 --> 00:16:41,471
so we want to know.

385
00:16:42,612 --> 00:16:43,333
AppSlayer had a bug.

386
00:16:44,334 --> 00:16:45,695
Our process was the same process.

387
00:16:45,735 --> 00:16:48,037
We didn't get any notice about the process failing.

388
00:16:48,537 --> 00:16:50,979
But AppSlayer had a bug, I think, about four months ago.

389
00:16:52,325 --> 00:16:53,646
And they just gave us double the data.

390
00:16:54,126 --> 00:16:56,988
So we ran the same process, nothing failed, no red flags,

391
00:16:57,388 --> 00:16:58,809
and we got double the installations.

392
00:16:59,750 --> 00:17:01,751
So either we were doing our job really, really good

393
00:17:01,771 --> 00:17:03,553
at marketing, or something was wrong.

394
00:17:03,973 --> 00:17:05,374
This is called a business anomaly.

395
00:17:05,934 --> 00:17:08,396
By the way, business anomalies can happen for a good reason.

396
00:17:08,456 --> 00:17:12,159
It could be that a new market opens up for you

397
00:17:12,279 --> 00:17:13,780
and users are really liking what you do,

398
00:17:13,820 --> 00:17:16,081
but it means that the KPI is behaving

399
00:17:16,121 --> 00:17:17,122
not in the way you'd expect.

400
00:17:18,114 --> 00:17:20,115
You can develop this in-house or you can use a tool

401
00:17:20,295 --> 00:17:23,016
that does that and we're using Anodot for that.

402
00:17:23,176 --> 00:17:24,656
By the way, we're working with King,

403
00:17:25,076 --> 00:17:26,437
we have a center in Barcelona,

404
00:17:26,977 --> 00:17:28,898
which is the Business Incident Management Center,

405
00:17:28,938 --> 00:17:29,638
I believe it's called,

406
00:17:30,178 --> 00:17:31,399
and we're working with the people there

407
00:17:31,459 --> 00:17:32,639
to learn how they're doing it.

408
00:17:33,251 --> 00:17:35,292
Now this is king and social point.

409
00:17:35,332 --> 00:17:37,653
These are big companies and we're still benefiting

410
00:17:38,354 --> 00:17:40,275
from buying things and not developing them in-house.

411
00:17:40,335 --> 00:17:43,637
So if you're a small studio and you wanna have analytics,

412
00:17:43,857 --> 00:17:45,258
but you don't have an analytics team

413
00:17:45,358 --> 00:17:48,039
and it doesn't make sense for you to have analytics team,

414
00:17:48,519 --> 00:17:49,700
use something like Delta DNA.

415
00:17:50,200 --> 00:17:51,521
You can still have analytics.

416
00:17:51,961 --> 00:17:53,462
You don't need to create everything in-house.

417
00:17:54,122 --> 00:17:55,123
There's enough services.

418
00:17:55,143 --> 00:17:57,845
Use a cloud, you don't need to develop a cloud.

419
00:17:57,905 --> 00:17:58,805
The world's come a long way.

420
00:17:59,786 --> 00:18:00,066
All right.

421
00:18:01,621 --> 00:18:04,664
Focus on value, BMF, product market fit.

422
00:18:05,244 --> 00:18:07,626
Product market fit is a very fancy way to say

423
00:18:07,766 --> 00:18:10,909
in lean startup terms that work on things

424
00:18:10,949 --> 00:18:11,970
that people care about.

425
00:18:13,191 --> 00:18:14,051
I'll give you an example.

426
00:18:15,052 --> 00:18:17,394
One of the things, one of the first researches

427
00:18:17,574 --> 00:18:19,015
that I saw from the data science team,

428
00:18:19,056 --> 00:18:21,638
I came into Social Point, what are we working on?

429
00:18:21,678 --> 00:18:22,719
And I talked to the scientists.

430
00:18:23,339 --> 00:18:25,701
One of them presented a model that was very clever.

431
00:18:25,901 --> 00:18:28,864
He was analyzing sentiment analysis.

432
00:18:28,924 --> 00:18:30,185
So how people were reacting

433
00:18:30,905 --> 00:18:32,246
to our games, to our versions.

434
00:18:32,346 --> 00:18:36,949
He took data from story views, social media, customer center.

435
00:18:37,009 --> 00:18:39,271
He built a very robust system that

436
00:18:39,311 --> 00:18:42,613
shows if people have a positive or negative response

437
00:18:42,673 --> 00:18:44,554
to versions, to changes that we're making.

438
00:18:45,215 --> 00:18:47,216
Amazing, super interesting.

439
00:18:47,737 --> 00:18:49,518
No one ever used it for anything.

440
00:18:50,238 --> 00:18:51,299
He did that analysis.

441
00:18:51,359 --> 00:18:52,140
It took a lot of time.

442
00:18:52,200 --> 00:18:53,060
It took a lot of data.

443
00:18:53,460 --> 00:18:54,261
It was very clever.

444
00:18:54,821 --> 00:18:56,422
No one in the games was waiting for that.

445
00:18:57,290 --> 00:18:59,612
No one in the games was using that as part of the decision

446
00:18:59,652 --> 00:19:02,953
making, it just sat there and became a very good article for

447
00:19:02,993 --> 00:19:07,816
the university. But that's it. So when you work on things, make

448
00:19:07,856 --> 00:19:11,698
sure there's a value attached to that. There is a caveat to

449
00:19:11,738 --> 00:19:14,239
that a lot of the things you do in analytics are a leap of

450
00:19:14,319 --> 00:19:19,541
faith. I'm not sure this will move the money needle. I'm not

451
00:19:19,641 --> 00:19:22,163
sure whether this will be something that is going to be

452
00:19:23,083 --> 00:19:25,484
major impact on the game.

453
00:19:26,390 --> 00:19:28,954
But even though you choose sometimes things

454
00:19:28,974 --> 00:19:31,197
that are a bit of a risk, make sure that you ask yourself,

455
00:19:31,918 --> 00:19:33,440
is this something, is this the best thing

456
00:19:33,481 --> 00:19:34,202
I could be doing now?

457
00:19:34,983 --> 00:19:37,666
This is true when you have 26 people like we have,

458
00:19:37,707 --> 00:19:38,988
and it's more true when you have one.

459
00:19:39,850 --> 00:19:41,572
What is the most important answer?

460
00:19:42,492 --> 00:19:43,633
I should be working on right now.

461
00:19:44,213 --> 00:19:46,775
Because if I'm working on the impact of the new maze,

462
00:19:46,875 --> 00:19:48,516
or the new island, or the new dragon,

463
00:19:48,996 --> 00:19:51,978
I'm not working on how to monetize existing users.

464
00:19:52,579 --> 00:19:54,720
So always make sure that you're very disciplined,

465
00:19:55,280 --> 00:19:58,002
and I'll show you how we do that in social points.

466
00:19:58,983 --> 00:20:00,804
One last thing, another trivial bit.

467
00:20:01,905 --> 00:20:02,845
Remember the big picture.

468
00:20:03,706 --> 00:20:04,927
When you're working on problems,

469
00:20:05,267 --> 00:20:07,869
we have a very strong tendency as people

470
00:20:08,489 --> 00:20:10,030
to focus on that problem.

471
00:20:10,769 --> 00:20:13,316
We were doing a morality analysis for one of our games.

472
00:20:14,515 --> 00:20:17,037
We had to intervene and make sure that analysis

473
00:20:17,117 --> 00:20:18,478
applies to other games.

474
00:20:18,898 --> 00:20:20,899
We were doing a new game with match threes.

475
00:20:21,460 --> 00:20:23,621
We had a game, a version that we launched

476
00:20:24,102 --> 00:20:25,223
for a game that we killed.

477
00:20:25,983 --> 00:20:28,405
The only reason we did that was not because

478
00:20:28,465 --> 00:20:29,646
that game would benefit from that,

479
00:20:29,686 --> 00:20:30,747
but we would get some learning

480
00:20:31,267 --> 00:20:32,348
for things we do in the future.

481
00:20:32,808 --> 00:20:34,549
Even if you only have one game in your life,

482
00:20:34,709 --> 00:20:36,271
I really hope you'll be making more games.

483
00:20:36,891 --> 00:20:39,233
Always remember, take something from it.

484
00:20:39,933 --> 00:20:43,015
Always try to do things in a way that benefits.

485
00:20:43,876 --> 00:20:49,042
other games. When you answer a question, who buys? Try to answer that question in a way that you can

486
00:20:49,082 --> 00:20:54,468
rewrite or rerun it in other games. This is really important when you're running analytics in a

487
00:20:54,508 --> 00:21:01,195
company. All right. So how do we at SocialPoint make sure that we don't lose focus? How do we

488
00:21:01,235 --> 00:21:03,017
make sure that when we're working on something,

489
00:21:03,756 --> 00:21:04,597
It's something interesting.

490
00:21:04,738 --> 00:21:06,400
Now I will say this, due diligence,

491
00:21:07,041 --> 00:21:08,924
I had two startups that were amazing

492
00:21:09,325 --> 00:21:10,346
and would have changed the world.

493
00:21:10,567 --> 00:21:13,010
I created an AI that plays games

494
00:21:13,171 --> 00:21:15,434
and does everything for you and was remarkable

495
00:21:16,075 --> 00:21:16,696
and no one bought it.

496
00:21:17,725 --> 00:21:22,790
Both of my startups ended as being very, very good experiences, but no one used them.

497
00:21:23,071 --> 00:21:27,175
Just because you think something is interesting, just because you think someone is going to

498
00:21:27,215 --> 00:21:28,836
use this, that's not the way.

499
00:21:29,257 --> 00:21:31,819
You need to make sure that you measure if someone is using this.

500
00:21:32,440 --> 00:21:34,201
And this is how we do that at SocialPoint.

501
00:21:35,182 --> 00:21:39,326
The chart that you're seeing here, remember I told you we took the super KPIs?

